notesStmt.note: Part one: fol. 1, upper margin lost; staining throughout, particularly in Part two; Part one dated 1472; Part two: circa 1450-1500, most likely circa 1470-1500
Quire 10 structure uncertain, likely -12, cancelled with no loss of text

msIdentifier.repository: Donald F. and Mildred Topp Othmer Library of Chemical History

msContents.summary: This manuscript contains a copy of one of the central early texts of the Pseudo-Lullian alchemical corpus, assembled before the sixteenth century from two independent manuscripts.

msItem.title: De Quarta inceratione per viam reductionis congelationis et subtiliationis
msItem.incipit: [A]b hinc vero sumatur quid sublimatum est … facere poteris adlibitum tamen intelligas magisterium.

msItem.title: Original rubric very faded and obscured by the (incorrect) title added by a later hand, De lapide Philosophico
msItem.incipit: Deus in virtute sancte trinitatis tue in qua vnitas tue diuinitatis non est in aliquo uulnerata … aqua ad duplum sulfuris fuerit perfecte rotata

support.watermark: Part one: unidentified bull's head with eyes above a rod ending in a one-line star; Part two: unidentified circle, cross within, and unidentified two-line snake on a column

supportDesc.extent: iii+105+i; 158 x 104 mm 164 x 104 mm bound to 168 x 114 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Contemporary foliation in red Arabic numerals middle top margin recto in the first text beginning on fol. 2 (upper margin fol. 1 lacking, presumably foliated), modern foliation in pencil, fols. 1-16, bottom outer corner recto, and then continuing in top outer corner, another set of modern foliation, bottom outer corner recto foliates the second text separately

p.catchwords: Part two: horizontal catchwords in lower margin (e.g., fol. 17v)

layoutDesc.layout: Fols. 1r-16v, no ruling apparent apart from full-length vertical bounding lines in blind; written area: 122 x 72 mm, thirty-two to thirty long lines
Fols. 17r-105v, frame-ruled with full-length vertical bounding lines only in lead; written area: 126-130 x 72 mm, twenty-four to twenty long lines

decoDesc.decoNote: Part one: nine drawings of alchemical instruments, charts and figures in red and brown; red rubrics throughout, majuscules stroked in red; Part two, very faded rubrics, two- to one-line pale red initials, manicules present in part 2 (e.g., fols. 18v, 19r)

3vPen-and ink illustrations, pitcher, labeled "monoculus raymundi"; a furnace, and an interior view of a furnace, labeled, "atthanor tripes arthanorum," and "Dominus Comes Archi ex sua industria nomine fransciscus [sic] anno lxxii"
11rIncipit, "B primum principium: aurum, argentum, natura vitrioli et salis, mercurius, … Z, separacio humoris"
11vCircular and triangular diagrams, most with letters
12rCircular and triangular diagrams, most with letters

12vCircle, enclosing four circles labeled, "aqua elementata, telea elementata, omnia et vnum, lex elementatus, ignis elelementatus"; below, incipit, "Hec est figura circularis ostendit quomodo elemente partificium …"; diagram of an alembic (labeled "lembicus magistri"), below, incipit, "Hec figura alembici ostendit qualiter …"; two circles labeled "sulfur" and "medicina," below, incipit, "Hec figura ostendit quomodo magisterium dividitur inter duas partes …"; three circles, labeled, "rubea coruptio," "generatio sulfuris" and "generatio me[ici]ne," incipit, "Hec figura …"
13rThree circles labeled, "liquefaccio, elementatio, diuisio,"; three circles labeled "inhumatio, distillacio, calcinacio," and three circles labeled "inceratio, congelatio, sublimatio"
13vTwo diagrams of circles, the first labeled, "figura fermentorum mistendorum"
14rDiagram of circles, with letters and interconnections, including aqua, aer, ignis, lapis, terra etc.
14vScala generationis primordialium materialum[?] in magisterio, etc. (twelve different scala on fols. 14v-15v)
15rScala generationis primordialium materialum[?] in magisterio, etc (twelve different scala on fols. 14v-15v)
15vScala generationis primordialium materialum[?] in magisterio, etc. (twelve different scala on fols. 14v-15v)
16rFigura quomodo ex triangulari et ex trangulis conponitur figura circuli
16vDiagram with concentric circles surrounding intersecting triangles, labeled materia confusa in the center

binding.p: Modern brown leather, front and back covers bordered by single gilt fillet, smooth spine letters "Lullius," marbled endpapers

history.provenance: Front flyleaf, fol. ii verso, "Bonaparte Carolos. A. Dom 1763, Advocacii civit"; Carlo Maria Buonaparte (27/29 March 1746– 24 February 1785), the father of the Emperor Napoleon, was a Corsican lawyer and politician who briefly served as a personal assistant of the revolutionary leader Pasquale Paoli, and later became Corsica's representative to the court of Louis XVI; Belonged to Joost R. Ritman (b. 1941), the Dutch businessman and collector of art and books; acquired from Laurence Witten, Southport, Connecticut in 1983; Bibliotheca Philosophia Hermetica MS 17 (bookplate inside front cover); briefly described in Medieval Manuscripts in Dutch Collections (Online Resources), and in Gumbert, 1987, no. 119-120
